g are central. The monograph is about the self and the other, inner and outer, own and strange; about borders and crossing borders, and about the sublime activities of passing and translating. Meir analyses and critically discusses the writings of great contemporary Jewish dialogical thinkers and argues that the values of interreligious theology are moored in their thoughts. In his view interreligious dialogue supposes attentive listening, humility, a critical attitude towards oneself and others, a good amount of self-relativism and humor. It is about proximity, dialogical reading, engagement and interconnectedness.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aHistoryxTopics in HistoryxJewish HistoryxJewish Thought. 0aJewish StudiesxJewish HistoryxJewish Thought. 0aJewish StudiesxJudaismxModern Times. 0aJewsxStudy and teachingxJewish HistoryxJewish Thought. 0aJewsxStudy and teachingxJudaismxModern Times. 0aPhilosophyxPhilosophy of Religion. 4aDialogisches Prinzip. 4aInterreligiöse Theologie. 4aJudentum. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2015z9783110438635oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831104305160 cprintz978311043931140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311043045540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110430455423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110430455.jpg  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA1